---
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const pkgs = (await getCollection('packages')).map((p) => p.data);
const link = (slug: string) => {
  const p = pkgs.find((x) => x.slug === slug);
  return p ? `<a href="/packages/${p.slug}">${p.name}</a>` : slug;
};

const withDeps = pkgs
  .filter((p) => p.family === 'supply-chain' && p.requires.length > 0)
  .sort((a, b) => a.requires.length - b.requires.length);

const questions = (await getCollection('compare'))
  .sort((a, b) => a.data.title.localeCompare(b.data.title));

const breadcrumbLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
  itemListElement: [
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: Astro.site!.href },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Supply-chain security' },
  ],
};
---

<Base
  title="PHP supply-chain security: Sigstore, provenance & attestations"
  description="How to verify and produce build provenance for PHP packages — a pure-PHP Sigstore verifier and signer, the attestation formats underneath, and Composer plugins."
>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbLd)} />
  </Fragment>

  <h1>Software supply-chain security for PHP</h1>

  <p>
    When you run <code>composer install</code>, you download and execute code from
    dozens of repositories. Nothing in the default toolchain checks <em>who</em>
    built each package or <em>how</em>. <code>composer.lock</code> pins a dist hash,
    so it gives you the same bytes every time — that's integrity, not provenance. If
    a release is malicious, the lock file faithfully pins the malicious hash.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Sigstore</strong> and <strong>build-provenance attestations</strong>
    close that gap: a signed statement that an artifact was built by a specific
    workflow in a specific repository, recorded in a public transparency log. These
    packages bring the full loop to PHP — producing it, consuming it, and the formats
    in between.
  </p>

  <h2>The stack</h2>
  <p>Each layer is a separate package, so you take only what you need:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Verify</strong> — <Fragment set:html={link('sigstore-verify')} />: certificate chain, transparency-log inclusion, timestamp, DSSE, identity policy.</li>
    <li><strong>Sign</strong> — <Fragment set:html={link('sigstore-sign')} />: keyful or keyless (Fulcio + ambient OIDC), producing a bundle.</li>
    <li><strong>Bundle &amp; log</strong> — <Fragment set:html={link('sigstore-bundle')} />, <Fragment set:html={link('rekor-client')} />.</li>
    <li><strong>Attestation formats</strong> — <Fragment set:html={link('dsse')} />, <Fragment set:html={link('in-toto-attestation')} />, <Fragment set:html={link('slsa-provenance')} />, <Fragment set:html={link('tuf')} />, <Fragment set:html={link('openvex')} />.</li>
    <li><strong>Signatures &amp; notes</strong> — <Fragment set:html={link('sshsig')} />, <Fragment set:html={link('signed-note')} />.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    No code needed to see it in action: the
    <a href="/tools/sigstore-bundle">bundle inspector</a> decodes and verifies a
    <code>.sigstore.json</code> right in the browser, running on these packages.
  </p>

  <h2>At install time</h2>
  <p>
    <Fragment set:html={link('composer-attest')} /> is a Composer plugin that verifies
    GitHub build-provenance attestations as packages are downloaded — checking that
    each dependency was really built by its repository's CI.
    <Fragment set:html={link('composer-license-gate')} /> gates dependency licenses
    against an allow/deny policy in the same install step.
  </p>
  <p>
    <a href="/guides/verify-provenance-at-install">Guide: verify provenance at install →</a> ·
    <a href="/guides/gate-dependency-licenses">Guide: gate licenses →</a> ·
    <a href="/tools/composer-attestations">Check any Packagist package online →</a>
  </p>

  <h2>How they build on each other</h2>
  <p>
    Each package depends only on the layers it needs — nothing pulls in the whole
    family. The k2gl dependencies of each supply-chain package:
  </p>
  <ul class="deps">
    {withDeps.map((p) => (
      <li>
        <a href={`/packages/${p.slug}`}>{p.name}</a> →{' '}
        {p.requires.map((r, i) => (
          <>{i > 0 ? ', ' : ''}<a href={`/packages/${r.name.replace('k2gl/', '')}`}>{r.name}</a></>
        ))}
      </li>
    ))}
  </ul>

  <h2>Common questions</h2>
  <ul>
    {questions.map((q) => (
      <li><a href={`/compare/${q.id}`}>{q.data.title}</a></li>
    ))}
  </ul>

  <h2>Conformance</h2>
  <p>
    The verifier and signer pass the official
    <a href="https://github.com/sigstore/sigstore-conformance">sigstore-conformance</a>
    suite for both verifying and signing. See the
    <a href="/blog/verify-composer-provenance">walkthrough</a> for the full loop on
    real packages.
  </p>

  <style>
    .deps { line-height: 2; }
    .deps li { margin: 0.15rem 0; }
  </style>
</Base>
